@startuml fig-quic-handshake
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title QUIC Connection Establishment (1-RTT and 0-RTT)

participant "Client" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server" as S #C8E6C9

== First connection (1-RTT) ==

C -[#1565C0]> S : **Initial**\nClientHello (TLS 1.3)\nQUIC transport parameters\n(over UDP)

S -[#1565C0]> C : **Initial + Handshake**\nServerHello\nEncrypted Extensions\nCertificate + Finished

C -[#43A047]> S : **Handshake Finished**

C <-[#333333]> S : Application data (encrypted)

== Subsequent connection (0-RTT) ==

C -[#FF9800]> S : **Initial + 0-RTT data**\nClientHello + cached key\n+ early application data

S -[#43A047]> C : **Handshake** + accept 0-RTT

note over C, S #FFF9C4
  0-RTT sends data with the very first packet
  (lower latency but vulnerable to replay)
end note

legend right
  QUIC runs over UDP and integrates TLS 1.3.
  The first connection requires one round trip.
  Subsequent connections may use 0-RTT
  for immediate data transmission.
  QUIC is the foundation of HTTP/3.
endlegend
@enduml
